;; tsfpp.cnj — TSF++ coding standard, recovered from source
;;
;; This file is NOT hand-authored the way dice-forge.cnj is. It was recovered
;; by reading the actual @tsfpp/* package source — not by summarising what the
;; standard is *called*, but by reading what it *enforces*: eslint rule
;; definitions, tsconfig compiler flags, the prelude's real exports, and two
;; real consuming modules (boundary). This is a manual, LLM-performed pass over
;; the exhume grimoire's recovery arc (x/recover-stack + x/infer-conventions),
;; not a literal invocation of those constructs as tools — there is no `x/`
;; runtime in this session, only the reasoning the grimoire describes, done by
;; hand against real files.
;;
;; Why this file exists: dice-forge.cnj originally named `:tsfpp-standard` as
;; an asset but gave it a fictional `:location` and a seven-bullet
;; architectural summary. The generator honoured what it was actually given —
;; functional core / imperative shell, Result<T,E> errors — and never received
;; the idiom-level rules (`absurd()` on every exhaustive switch, `type` never
;; `interface`) because those were named in prose, never given as enforceable
;; content. This file is the fix: the standard, recovered from its own
;; enforcement config and its own source code, so the next materialisation is
;; handed the actual rules instead of a label pointing at them.
;;
;; Recovered from (private repositories, snapshotted into this repo's tmp/
;; on 2026-07-09 for this recovery pass — not a public URL, see :location
;; below):
;;   @tsfpp/standard       v1.3.0   — CODING_STANDARD.md, REACT_CODING_STANDARD.md,
;;                                    PHILOSOPHY.md, RATIONALE.md, DEVIATIONS.md
;;   @tsfpp/prelude        v1.7.0   — src/fp.ts (the full FP vocabulary)
;;   @tsfpp/boundary       v1.2.0   — src/boundary-types.ts, boundary-handler.ts,
;;                                    boundary-idempotency.ts
;;   @tsfpp/tsconfig       v1.0.0   — tsconfig.base/lib/app.json
;;   @tsfpp/eslint-config  v1.0.1   — base.ts, react.ts, api.ts, README.md
;;
;; Evidence hierarchy honoured throughout (per exhume's :attested / :strongly-
;; inferred / :speculative grading): an eslint rule that fails the build is
;; firmer evidence than a doc's prose description of the same rule, which is
;; firmer than a pattern merely observed in code. Every :enforces/:prohibits
;; entry below traces to an enforcement-config line or a directly-read source
;; file, not to a paraphrase of a paraphrase.
;;
;; On a practitioner grimoire: I considered packaging conformance-by-
;; construction spells (e.g. a `tsfpp/adt` spell that always emits absurd(),
;; a `tsfpp/boundary` spell that always emits the Result-shaped handler) as a
;; third layer beyond this asset + lore. Deferred, deliberately — the two
;; failures actually observed (missing absurd(), interface instead of type)
;; are idiom-level rules that were simply never given to the generator, not
;; failures of architectural scaffolding. A rich, honest asset plus load-
;; bearing lore closes that gap; a spell library is machinery for a problem
;; this file already solves. Perfect is the enemy of good — revisit only if
;; the asset + lore combination is tried and still falls short in practice.

;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; SECTION 1 — THE BASE STANDARD
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(asset :tsfpp-standard
  :type        :code-standard
  :description "TSF++ (TypeScript Functional++) — a functional-core /
                imperative-shell TypeScript standard in the JSF++/JPL Power-
                of-Ten lineage, adapted for ML/Haskell-style totality and
                exhaustiveness. Five axioms: correctness by construction,
                totality, immutability, referential transparency,
                exhaustiveness. Embodied (not just described) by the
                @tsfpp/prelude and @tsfpp/boundary packages, and mechanically
                enforced by @tsfpp/eslint-config and @tsfpp/tsconfig."
  :language    :typescript
  :location    "Private repositories: tsfpp/standard, tsfpp/prelude,
                tsfpp/boundary, tsfpp/tsconfig, tsfpp/eslint-config —
                not publicly fetchable; recovered from a source snapshot,
                see provenance note above. Do not re-derive a public URL
                for this asset without confirming one exists."
  :version     "1.3.0 (spec) — prelude 1.7.0, boundary 1.2.0,
                eslint-config 1.0.1, tsconfig 1.0.0"
  :recovered-from "tmp/{standard,prelude,boundary,tsconfig,eslint-config}
                   snapshot, recovery pass 2026-07-09"
  :confidence  :attested   ;; read directly from enforcement config and source,
                           ;; not inferred from usage patterns
  :enforces    [
    ;; ── Type system ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    "Illegal states are unrepresentable: mutually exclusive data is modelled
     as a discriminated union, never as independent optional flags (Rule 1.1)"
    "Every switch over a discriminated union's tag is exhaustive, verified by
     `@typescript-eslint/switch-exhaustiveness-check`, and its default/else
     branch calls `absurd(x)` on the now-`never`-narrowed remainder — not a
     bare `default: break`, not an unreachable-code comment (Rules 1.2/4.1,
     backed by `absurd` from @tsfpp/prelude)"
    "`type` aliases only for all object/union shapes — never `interface`,
     enforced by `@typescript-eslint/consistent-type-definitions: ['error','type']`
     (Rule 1.4)"
    "No `any` (Rule 1.5, `@typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any`)"
    "No `!` non-null assertions and no `as` type assertions, except inside a
     single guarded smart-constructor function per branded type — the sole
     permitted cast site, `eslint-disable`-flagged and commented
     `DEVIATION(1.6)` (Rule 1.6, `consistent-type-assertions: 'never'`)"
    "No `enum` — string-literal unions or `as const` objects instead (Rule 1.8)"
    "No `namespace`, no `instanceof`, no `class`, no `this`, no `new` outside
     an explicitly commented adapter boundary (Rule 1.9)"

    ;; ── Immutability & function shape ────────────────────────────────────
    "No `let` — `const` only (Rule 2.1, `functional/no-let`)"
    "Deep `readonly` on every type; no property mutation, no array-mutation
     methods, no parameter reassignment (Rules 2.2/2.3,
     `functional/immutable-data`, `functional/prefer-readonly-type`)"
    "Explicit return type on every exported function — never inferred
     (Rule 3.1, `explicit-function-return-type`)"
    "Function arity ≤ 3; a fourth-or-more parameter is a readonly options
     record instead (Rule 3.2, `max-params: 3`)"
    "Cyclomatic complexity ≤ 10, nesting depth ≤ 4, function body ≤ 40 lines,
     one concern per function (Rule 3.4 — a bundled budget, not four separate
     rules: `complexity`, `max-depth`, `max-lines-per-function`)"
    "No imperative loops — `map`/`filter`/`reduce`/recursion or the prelude's
     `List<A>` combinators (Rule 4.2, `functional/no-loop-statements`)"
    "Strict boolean expressions (no truthiness-checking non-booleans) and
     `===`/`!==` only, never `==`/`!=` (Rule 4.5)"

    ;; ── Errors & effects ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
    "No `throw` outside an explicitly commented adapter boundary — errors and
     absence are modelled as `Result<T,E>` and `Option<A>` from @tsfpp/prelude,
     not exceptions (Rule 6.2, `functional/no-throw-statements`)"
    "No unhandled promise rejections; no misused promises (Rule 6.4,
     `no-floating-promises`, `no-misused-promises`)"
    "Effectful capabilities (logging, storage) are consumed through a
     structurally-typed port (e.g. `Logger`) and injected at the composition
     root — never imported as a concrete library at the point of use
     (embodied by @tsfpp/prelude's Logger port, PHILOSOPHY.md's library-
     compatibility stance)"
    "Every sanctioned rule exception is a `// DEVIATION(rule-number):
     <one-line reason>` comment at the callsite; a deviation that applies
     project-wide additionally gets a dated, reviewed entry in DEVIATIONS.md,
     with `active` / `superseded` / `revoked` status"

    ;; ── File & module hygiene ────────────────────────────────────────────
    "File length ≤ 400 lines, 800 as an absolute DEVIATION(11.2)-flagged
     ceiling (Rule 11.2, `max-lines`)"
    "`import type` for type-only imports (`consistent-type-imports`,
     paired with `verbatimModuleSyntax`/`isolatedModules` in tsconfig.base)"]

  :prohibits   [
    "`interface` declarations without a DEVIATION(1.4) comment"
    "`any`, bare `!`, and `as` type assertions outside a guarded smart-
     constructor body"
    "`enum`, `namespace`, `instanceof`, `new` outside an adapter facade,
     `class`-based OOP, `this`"
    "`let` or any local/shared mutable state"
    "A `switch`/`if`-chain over a union's tag that does not end by narrowing
     to `never` and calling `absurd()` — this is the single most common way
     generated code silently drifts from this standard: the switch looks
     exhaustive today and stops being exhaustive the moment a union member
     is added, with no compiler error, because nothing forced the default
     branch to prove there was nothing left"
    "`throw` in business logic"
    "Concrete library types (a logger, a store) imported directly into
     domain/application code instead of behind a port"]

  :applies-to  [:library :spa :test-suite]
  :agent       :typescript-specialist-agent
  :active-in   :project)

;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; SECTION 2 — THE REACT PROFILE
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; A separate asset, not folded into :tsfpp-standard, because it is a
;; distinct document (REACT_CODING_STANDARD.md) with its own rule numbering
;; (1.1–18.4) layered ON TOP of the base standard — every base rule still
;; applies unchanged to .tsx code. Keeping it separate means a target that
;; is pure TypeScript (no React) references only :tsfpp-standard, and a
;; target with a UI layer references both.

(asset :tsfpp-react
  :type        :code-standard
  :description "TSF++/React — the React profile of TSF++. Six axioms specific
                to UI code: render is a pure function of props/state; state is
                a liability, justify every piece against an elimination
                ladder; the component tree is a value; `useEffect` is React's
                `goto`; state management is a hierarchy, not a choice; the
                compiler/types/linter prove what tests cannot."
  :language    :typescript
  :location    "Private repository tsfpp/standard, spec/REACT_CODING_STANDARD.md —
                see :tsfpp-standard's :location note; same provenance."
  :version     "1.0.0"
  :recovered-from "tmp/standard/spec/REACT_CODING_STANDARD.md, read in full,
                   recovery pass 2026-07-09"
  :confidence  :attested
  :enforces    [
    ;; A target names exactly one :standard asset (see core.md's target
    ;; signature — no multi-standard slot exists), so this asset restates
    ;; the two base-standard rules most load-bearing for UI code rather than
    ;; only cross-referencing :tsfpp-standard. The base standard still
    ;; applies in full to .tsx files; these two are repeated here because
    ;; they are exactly the ones a generator misses when a target's
    ;; :standard points only at the React profile.
    "Exhaustive switches over a discriminated union end in `absurd(x)` on the
     `never`-narrowed default — identical discipline to base Rule 1.2/4.1,
     restated because it applies to render logic and reducers too"
    "`type` aliases only, never `interface` — identical to base Rule 1.4,
     restated for the same reason"

    "Components are `const` arrow functions with an explicit
     `ReactElement | ReactNode | null` return type — never `function`
     declarations or classes (React Rules 1.1/1.2)"
    "Props are `type` aliases suffixed `Props`, every field `readonly`; a
     variant-driven component's mutually exclusive prop sets are a
     discriminated union, never independent optional flags — the same
     illegal-states-unrepresentable discipline as base Rule 1.1, applied to
     props (React Rules 2.1/2.2)"
    "Every piece of state is justified against the elimination ladder before
     introduction: derivable from props/state → URL → server data (TanStack
     Query) → form state (React Hook Form) → local `useState` → lifted to a
     parent → context/store — in that order, skipping a rung only with a
     `DEVIATION(3.1)` comment (React Rule 3.1)"
    "`useEffect` only synchronises with systems outside React (subscriptions,
     browser APIs, imperative third-party libraries); it must never derive
     state, fetch data, or react to a user event, and every subscribing
     effect returns a cleanup function with an exhaustive dependency array
     (React Rules 4.1–4.6)"
    "`useMemo`/`useCallback`/`React.memo` require one of three documented
     reasons (referential identity for a memoized consumer, profiled expense,
     a hook dependency) — never speculative (React Rule 5.1)"
    "Server reads go through TanStack Query with a typed query-key factory;
     mutations return `Result<T,E>`-shaped outcomes; no raw `fetch` in
     component code (React Rules 7.1–7.3)"
    "Non-trivial forms use React Hook Form with a Zod schema as the single
     source of truth; submit handlers return `Promise<Result<T, FormError>>`,
     never throw (React Rules 8.1/8.2)"
    "Global state exists only after the elimination ladder is exhausted;
     Zustand for store-shaped state, Jotai for fine-grained atomic state;
     consumers select narrowly, never the whole store (React Rules 3.6,
     10.1–10.5)"
    "Tailwind utilities for layout/spacing/colour; variants via `cva`, never
     inline class-string concatenation; design tokens only, never hex codes
     or magic pixel values inline (React Rules 11.1–11.4)"
    "Interactive elements are semantic HTML, never a `div` with a click
     handler; every form control has an associated label; keyboard
     navigation works for every flow (React Rules 16.1–16.3)"
    "Component tests query by accessible role via React Testing Library;
     network is mocked with MSW, never by stubbing `fetch` (React Rules
     17.1/17.3)"]

  :prohibits   [
    "Class components or `function`-declared components"
    "Optional-flag props for mutually exclusive variants"
    "Server state or URL-shaped state in `useState`"
    "`useEffect` for derived state, data fetching, or user-event reactions"
    "An effect that subscribes without returning a cleanup function"
    "Speculative memoisation with no documented reason"
    "Per-field `useState` in forms"
    "Whole-store selection (`useStore((s) => s)`)"
    "Inline hex codes or pixel literals in `className`"
    "A `div`/`span` with an `onClick` standing in for a semantic interactive
     element"]

  :applies-to  [:spa]
  :agent       :typescript-specialist-agent
  :active-in   :project)

;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; SECTION 3 — IDIOM LORE
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Where the assets above state RULES, this lore states IDIOMS — the shape
;; those rules take in practice, evidenced by real code. This is the layer
;; that was missing before: dice-forge.cnj's old asset said "exhaustive
;; switches" in prose; nothing ever showed the generator what an exhaustive
;; switch that actually satisfies the rule looks like, in real TSF++ code,
;; contrasted with the failure mode actually observed.

(lore tsfpp-idioms
  :observed-in ["tmp/prelude/src/fp.ts (absurd, Option/Result, pipe/comp/flow,
                 Map/Set combinators, Logger port)"
                "tmp/boundary/src/boundary-idempotency.ts (live absurd() usage
                 in a real discriminated-union switch)"
                "tmp/boundary/src/boundary-types.ts (branded-ID smart
                 constructors, ApiError taxonomy, RFC 9457 ProblemDetails)"
                "tmp/eslint-config/base.ts + README.md (every rule's
                 enforcement mechanism and canonical DEVIATION examples)"
                "tmp/standard/spec/{PHILOSOPHY,RATIONALE,DEVIATIONS}.md"]

  :patterns [
    {:name      :exhaustive-switch-via-absurd
     :when      "branching over a discriminated union's tag/kind field"
     :apply     "switch on the tag; every case returns; the default branch
                 calls `absurd(value)` on the now-`never`-narrowed remainder.
                 Real example (boundary-idempotency.ts):

                   switch (lookup.kind) {
                     case 'replay':        return mkReplayResponse(lookup.response);
                     case 'in_flight':     return mkInFlightResponse(parsedInput.input.traceId);
                     case 'key_conflict':  return mkConflictResponse(parsedInput.input.traceId);
                     case 'first_request': return executeFirstRequest({ store, handler, req, input: parsedInput.input });
                     default:              return absurd(lookup);
                   }

                 Never a bare `default: break`, never an unreachable-code
                 comment, never an omitted default relying on the linter alone."
     :rationale "`switch-exhaustiveness-check` catches a missing case at lint
                 time, but only if the default branch narrows to `never` —
                 `absurd(x: never): never` is that narrowing, made a runtime
                 assertion too. Adding a fifth `lookup.kind` variant later and
                 forgetting to handle it becomes a compile error at the
                 `absurd()` call site, not a silent fall-through. This is the
                 exact idiom the earlier dice-forge asset named
                 ('exhaustive switches') without ever showing — the generator
                 wrote switches, just not ones that end this way."}

    {:name      :type-over-interface
     :when      "declaring any object shape — props, DTOs, domain records,
                 branded IDs, discriminated unions"
     :apply     "a `type` alias, always. `interface` requires a
                 `// DEVIATION(1.4): <reason>` comment plus an eslint-disable,
                 and is reserved for the rare case of a genuine structural-
                 extension contract (e.g. augmenting a third-party ambient
                 type) — not a stylistic default."
     :rationale "`type` composes with unions and mapped types the way
                 discriminated-union modelling requires; `interface`'s
                 declaration-merging is exactly the kind of implicit,
                 order-dependent extension the standard's correctness-by-
                 construction axiom rules out. This is the second concrete
                 failure the earlier dice-forge asset caused: 'the code was
                 generated with interface' happened because nothing told the
                 generator this was a hard rule with a mechanical enforcement,
                 not a style preference."}

    {:name      :smart-constructor-centralises-the-cast
     :when      "constructing a branded/nominal type (e.g. `TraceId`,
                 `IdempotencyKey`) from a raw, unvalidated primitive"
     :apply     "exactly one function per branded type performs the `as`
                 cast, immediately after a runtime validation, flagged
                 `eslint-disable-next-line` and commented `DEVIATION(1.6)`.
                 Real example (boundary-types.ts):

                   export const mkTraceId = (raw: string): Option<TraceId> =>
                     raw.length > 0 ? some(raw as TraceId) : none;
                     // eslint-disable-line @typescript-eslint/consistent-type-assertions
                     // -- DEVIATION(1.6): smart-constructor body

                 Every other call site receives a `TraceId`, never a raw
                 `string`, and never casts one itself."
     :rationale "Centralising the one escape hatch (the cast) behind a
                 validated constructor means the type system can be trusted
                 everywhere else in the codebase — a `TraceId` in hand really
                 was validated, because there is exactly one place it could
                 have been minted. The same centralising instinct recurs for
                 collections: @tsfpp/prelude's `intoMap`/`intoSet` are the
                 sole sanctioned `new Map()`/`new Set()` call sites; everyone
                 else consumes the immutable result."}

    {:name      :ports-not-libraries
     :when      "a boundary needs an effectful capability — logging, a
                 store, a clock"
     :apply     "declare a small structurally-typed port (@tsfpp/prelude's
                 `Logger` — `{debug, info, warn, error}` typed methods over a
                 `LogEntry`) and depend on the port type; inject a concrete
                 implementation (pino, console, a test double) at the
                 composition root, never import the concrete library into
                 domain or application code."
     :rationale "A port is duck-typed against structure, not a class hierarchy
                 — swapping the concrete logger requires no code change where
                 the port is consumed, and a test can inject a silent logger
                 with no mocking framework. This is the standard's
                 correctness-by-construction axiom applied to dependencies:
                 the compiler enforces the contract, not a convention."}]

  :anti-patterns [
    {:name    :switch-without-absurd
     :avoid   "a `default` branch that returns a fallback value, breaks
               silently, or is omitted and left to the linter alone"
     :because "the single most common way generated TSF++-flavoured code
               silently stops being TSF++: it compiles, it runs, it looks
               exhaustive — until a union member is added, and nothing
               catches the gap because nothing forced the default to prove
               there was nothing left to handle"}

    {:name    :interface-for-convenience
     :avoid   "reaching for `interface` because a shape 'might need to
               extend later' or out of habit from non-TSF++ TypeScript"
     :because "declaration merging is implicit, order-dependent extension —
               exactly the class of surprise the standard's axioms exist to
               rule out. If genuine structural extension is needed, that is
               a DEVIATION(1.4), decided and commented, not a default"}

    {:name    :scattered-type-assertions
     :avoid   "an `as Brand` (or any `as`) appearing anywhere outside a
               single, named, guarded smart-constructor function"
     :because "every scattered cast is an unaudited claim that bypassed
               validation; centralising to one constructor per brand means
               there is exactly one place to check when a bad value turns up"}

    {:name    :effect-for-derived-or-fetched-state
     :avoid   "a `useEffect` that computes a value from props/state, calls
               `fetch`, or reacts to a click"
     :because "(React profile) all three have direct, effect-free
               alternatives — compute during render, TanStack Query, an
               event handler — and reaching for `useEffect` first is the
               React profile's named anti-pattern: 'useEffect is the goto
               of React'"}]

  :active-in :session)

;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; SECTION 4 — RECOVERED FINDINGS (drift, recorded honestly, not resolved)
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Per the exhume grimoire's discipline: when the evidence disagrees with
;; itself, the disagreement is the finding. These are NOT silently corrected
;; here — that would be improving-while-exhuming, the grimoire's named anti-
;; pattern. They are recorded so a practitioner applying this standard knows
;; where the source itself is inconsistent.

;; FINDING 1 — a real DEVIATION-comment mislabelling inside @tsfpp/prelude.
;;
;; @tsfpp/eslint-config's base.ts (line 59) and its own README.md (line 191)
;; both attest, unambiguously: Rule 1.4 is "prefer type over interface";
;; Rule 1.6 is "no `as`". @tsfpp/boundary's boundary-types.ts correctly cites
;; DEVIATION(1.6) at all five of its smart-constructor `as`-casts. But
;; @tsfpp/prelude's fp.ts cites DEVIATION(1.4) at its three equivalent
;; `as`-casts — `mkEvery` (line 219), `mkAny` (line 224), and `toObject`
;; (line 849) — for the identical pattern. Confidence: :attested (direct
;; three-way comparison of base.ts's own rule comments, the README's
;; canonical example, and both packages' actual source). This looks like a
;; copy-paste labelling slip in the prelude package that was never caught,
;; not a documented, deliberate deviation from the boundary package's
;; convention. Left as a finding, not fixed here — @tsfpp/prelude is not
;; this repository's to edit.

;; FINDING 2 — a version-pin drift between boundary and prelude.
;;
;; @tsfpp/boundary's package.json pins @tsfpp/prelude at ^1.6.0; prelude's
;; own CHANGELOG shows 1.7.0 released (adds `isDefined` and `toObject`).
;; Confidence: :attested that the pin and the release both exist;
;; :speculative whether boundary's code actually needs anything 1.7.0-only —
;; not verified here. Recorded as x/recover-stack's :detect-drift would:
;; the declared constraint and the available release disagree; the
;; disagreement is the finding, not silently resolved either way.

;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; How a consuming .cnj should reference this file
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;;
;; `target`'s `:standard` parameter names exactly one asset (core.md's
;; signature has no multi-standard slot) — so pick the one asset that
;; actually governs each target's artefacts:
;;
;; A target that produces pure TypeScript library code:
;;   (target :core :standard :tsfpp-standard ...)
;;
;; A target that produces a React SPA — :tsfpp-react is self-contained for
;; this purpose: it restates the two base rules most often missed (absurd,
;; type-over-interface) alongside its own React-specific rules, so a single
;; :standard reference is sufficient:
;;   (target :app :standard :tsfpp-react ...)
